To all you philosophers out there; time to earn your bread...

I probably have an old car battery laying about somewhere.  It's taking
up space in the garage.  I could use that extra room to get rid of it.
Now, I could drive down to the local gas station which is about 5 miles
down the road or I could dump it along the side of the road in a
drainage ditch which is only 1 or 2 miles down the road.  Driving to
the gas station is a pain you know when I could be playing on the
Internet instead.  If I drive to the gas station to "properly" dispose
of it, I'll miss probably 20 minutes of Internet time.  If I dump it
somewhere close I may only miss 5-10 minutes.  Of course if I drop it
in a drainage ditch the acid will eventually flow out into the local
eco-system or whatever it is we suburbanites have.  If I properly
dispose of it, maybe it could be chemically neutralized and its
constituent components returned harmlessly to the environment, I don't
know.  But what effect is that going to have on me if I dump it along
the side of the road?

Anyway, I really like doodling around on the Internet and am wondering
if there is any substantial reason at all why I should NOT dump the
battery along the side of the road somewhere.

Also I have another question for the enlightened.  I've been pretty
regularly donating blood for a few years now.  And I am now wondering
why should I bother doing this?  I could think of a lot more
entertaining things to do with my time.  In fact, I'm wondering why I
should do any charitable things.  What am *I* getting out of it?  I
could just as easily stop doing charitable things.  No big deal.  I
mean, why am I even doing them to begin with?  Is there any marked
difference at all between me and a guy who has never done a charitable
act in his life?
</POST>
