Finally a somewhat 'worthwhile' post by our Mr. Childress [:)]...though of
course, cloaked in the facetiousness of his wry humor.  The question has
been tossed around here from time to time and it is about Altruistic
behavior.  Right?

Most rational models of human behavior I believe take the 'self interest'
approach.  Much of social science is based upon this rational model where a
person acts to maximize their personal gains [or to minimize their losses].
If we took these models 'absolutely', we'd all be doing just as Mr.
Childress suggests...throwing our batteries into the nearest ditch rather
than expend the extra energy to take them for proper disposal.   And our
local blood banks would have gone dry long ago as well.

2 Salient excerpts from Wikipedia:
"Neitzche asserts that altruism is predicated on the assumption that others
are more important than one's self and that such a position is degrading and
demeaning. He also claims that it was very uncommon for people in Europe to
consider the sacrifice of one's own interests for others as virtuous until
after the advent of Christianity. Ayn Rand argued that altruism is the
willful sacrifice of one's values, and represents the reversal of morality
because only rationally selfish ethics allow one to pursue the values
required for human life."

I think both of these people were idiots however [especially Rand].  Most
people exist with conscience and some sense of duty back to the whole and
need not defend such 'socially responsible' existence.  That intellectuals
could unravel such 'responsible behavior' and actually argue to dismantle
conscience should be eye opening to us that the intellect should always be
held highly suspect and always accountable to that conscience BEFORE our
conscience is accountable to it.

In fact, I think a deeper explanation of altruism comes by way of a
discussion of "Conscience"...what it is, how it is.  I think a clue [not in
Wikipedia] is to look at our mammalarian trait to 'nuture' our young.  That
trait, honed to elevated levels, inspires an 'emotional' state whereby
'self' is abstracted 'into' the group.  A parent sacrificing for their young
is no great thing to understand.  And the individual sacrificing for the
whole is extrapolated from this innate nature of the animal, to become
defining of the human [as conscience].

But it is emotional in origin I believe...this binding force that ties us.
I say fuck Neitzche and Rand and the horse they rode in upon.  The
intellectual, present and past, would dismantle that conscience and thereby,
revert us to dumb animals with no redemptive qualities whatsoever [and
cruelty maximized...not to mention let's trash the countryside]. Another
reason I hold onto my Christian roots OUT OF CHOICE. And Wikipedia is
becoming tyrannical in scope BTW [another important subject].
