Great question.  You've found a new and interesting twist to the 'why
be moral?' question.  Note that for a reason to be 'substantial', it
has to be one you find convincing.  Lots of reasons have been given by
philosophers in the past, but no one finds any one of them convincing.
They can be roughly assigned to five different groups:
1)  Social:  Someone will see you, not like it, and do something to
you; or tell the owner, who'll do something to you.
2) Legal: Someone will see you and 'report it to the proper
authorities', who'll do the same.
3) Religious: a god will see you and do the same.
3) Psychological: Some will tell you that you're motivated by other
things than self-interest - empathy and honor are biggies - and that
either you'll feel guilt after the fact, or you're a psychopath.
4) Ethical: Some will offer you reasons why it is in your self-interest
to have (and therefore support) a system where people do not inflict
their garbage on others..

